            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How Mississippi income tax works</h2>
              <p>
                Mississippi is in the process of phasing out its individual
                income tax. The state has already eliminated the lowest brackets
                and is moving toward a single flat rate on taxable income, with
                the long‑term goal of full repeal if revenues allow.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on
                <strong>Mississippi state income tax</strong> only. It does not
                include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Federal income tax</li>
                <li>Social Security and Medicare (FICA)</li>
                <li>Local or municipal taxes</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Current Mississippi tax rates (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                Mississippi has historically used a progressive bracket system,
                but recent legislation has flattened and reduced the tax:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>2022:</strong> First $5,000 of taxable income exempt;
                  4% on the next $5,000; 5% above that.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2023:</strong> First $10,000 exempt; 5% on taxable
                  income above $10,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2024 and later (phase‑out path):</strong> Lawmakers
                  have signaled a move toward a lower flat rate and eventual
                  elimination, subject to revenue triggers. For planning, we
                  model a <strong>flat 4.7%–5% range</strong> on taxable income
                  above the exempt threshold, depending on year.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because the phase‑out details and timing can change with new
                legislation, always confirm the latest official rates with the
                <a
                  href="https://www.dor.ms.gov/individual"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Mississippi Department of Revenue</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>Formula used by this calculator</h3>
              <p>We estimate Mississippi taxable income as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Annualize income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If you enter pay per period, we convert to annual income:<br />
                  \[ \text{Annual gross} = \text{Pay per period} \times
                  \text{Number of periods per year} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Adjust for pre‑tax deductions</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{MS adjusted income} = \text{Annual gross} -
                  \text{Pre‑tax deductions} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Step 3 – Subtract deductions and exemptions</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{MS taxable income} = \max\bigl(0,\ \text{MS adjusted
                  income} - D - E\bigr) \] where:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>D</strong> = Mississippi standard or itemized
                    deductions (you can override).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>E</strong> = Mississippi personal exemptions (you
                    can override).
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Step 4 – Apply the Mississippi tax rate</strong></p>
                <p>
                  For a flat‑rate year: \[ \text{MS tax} = \text{Rate} \times
                  \max(0,\ \text{MS taxable income} - T) \] where
                  <strong>T</strong> is the exempt threshold (e.g., $10,000 in
                  2023).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Assumptions and limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool uses a simplified model of Mississippi deductions
                  and exemptions to keep the interface fast and easy.
                </li>
                <li>
